fields.descriptive_line: Bisque headed doll called Mabel, with blonde wig and blue eyes, on a calico body; unmarked, made in Germany, 1885
fields.physical_description:
[doll] Doll representing a caucausian female with moulded and painted facial features, a blonde mohair wig stitched in circles on a canvas base, and fixed blue glass eyes.  She has a bisque shoulder head on a wasp-waisted calico body.  The body is seamed at the sides and centre front and back; it has a double row of stitching across the top of the legs to allow the doll to be seated more easily.  The bisque arms are attached to the body by upper arms of calico on strips of cloth; the hands have separated thumbs with the fingers indicated in the moulding.  The legs are made entirely of cloth.
[dress] Doll's short dress of unlined velveteen printed with a millefleurs design of flowers and foliage in red, tan, green, white and black on a black ground.  The dress has a round neck trimmed with a flounce of machine made lace, and wrist-length sleeves with a turn-back cuff of similar lace. The garment is cut in a loose unwaisted style, with a frill of matching fabric at the hem; it fastens with a hook at the neck and an attached sash of matching fabric that ties at thigh level to make a low waisted effect.
[petticoat] Doll's waist petticoat of white cotton, gathered into a matching waistband, the short skirt finished with five horizontal tucks above the hem.  The garment fastens at the back of the waist with tying strings of white cotton tape.
[hat] Doll's round low-crowned hat of glazed plaited straw.  The short brim is partly turned up and is lined with embroidered net.  The hat has its original band of dark red ribbon around the base of the crown and holding the turned up brim; a large bow of wide ribbon with alternating panels of plaid and floral patterns has been added.
[drawers] Doll's white cotton drawers gathered into a plain waistband of matching fabric, each leg trimmed with a band of tatting at the hem.  The garment is open down the back and fastens  at the back of the waistband with a cloth covered button and a stitched buttonhole.
[chemise] Doll's white cotton chemise edged with tatting at the neck and armholes.  The garment fastens at the back with a pearl button and a stitched loop.
[stocking] Doll's Stocking of machine-knitted dark brown mercerised cotton yarn with two lines of cream-coloured yarn at the top. The stocking is a tube of fabric stitched together at the centre back, without a turned heel or reinforced toes.
[stocking] Doll's Stocking of machine-knitted dark brown mercerised cotton yarn with two lines of cream-coloured yarn at the top. The stocking is a tube of fabric stitched together at the centre back, without a turned heel or reinforced toes.
[shirt] Doll's shirt.  (From original [1962] record red and white cotton, part of a sports outfit)
[skirt] Doll's skirt.  (From original [1962] record red and white cotton, part of a sports outfit)
[hat] Doll's hat.  (From original [1962] record, tam o'shanter knitted in purple wool)
[hat] Doll's hat.  (From original [1962] record, navy velvet tam o'shanter)
[skirt] Doll's skirt.  (From original [1962] record  part of a navy blue sailor outfit)
[blouse] Doll's blouse.  (From original [1962] record  part of a navy blue sailor outfit)
[dress] Doll's dress of unlined cotton printed with sprigs of red flowers and black foliage on an ivory-coloured ground.  The dress has a rounded neck and wrist-length sleeves, all edged with tatting; the partly gathered skirt is attached to the bodice at the natural waistline.  The garment fastens at the back of the bodice with hooks and stitched loops.
[drawers] Pair of doll's open drawers, of white linen.  The legs are lightly gathered into a waistband of matching fabric, and finished at the hem with two horizontal tucks and picot edging.  The garment fastens at the back of the waistband.
[petticoat] Doll's waist petticoat of white cotton lawn, gathered into a matching waistband, the short skirt finished at the hem with a band of whitework embroidery between bands of horizontal tucks.  The garment fastens at the back of the waist with a fabric covered button and stitched buttonhole.
[nightshirt] Doll's nightshirt of white linen, with a round neck and stand collar; the wrist length sleeves are shaped by unpressed pleats half way along the inner seam.
[petticoat] Doll's waist petticoat of cream-coloured flannelette, lightly pleated into a cotton waistband of matching colour.  The short skirt is finished with a row of featherstitching in cream coloured thread above a blanket-stitched hem.  The garment fastens at the back of the waist with a fabric covered button and stitched buttonhole.
[dress] Doll's dress of white linen, with a high round neck finished with a frill of white cutwork edging, and long sleeves with cuffs of similar cutwork edging.  The bodice is gathered at the neck and waist, with the attached skirt gathered only at the sides and back.  The skirt has three horizontal bands of applied white cotton bias cut tape, and is finished at the hem with a deep scalloped frill of white cotton which is hand worked with white cutwork embroidery featuring flat-faced flowers with sixteen petals.
[nightdress] White cotton nightdress with a ruffled neck and matching wrist-length sleeves.  The fullness of the garment front is gathered into a panel of cutwork embroidery at the waist, to which a tie sash is attached at each side and finished with a vertical row of featherstitch.  The garment fastens at the back with a drawstring at the neck
[chemise] Doll's chemise of white cotton with a rounded neck and armholes, all edged with lace.

fields.history_note:
Doll called Mabel, given by Miss F Ashbee (RF 61/1861) and likely to have belonged originally to her mother as a child. (Jane) Felicity Ashbee was born 22/02/1913 and died 26/07/2008, the daughter of the architect and craftsman C R (Charles Robert) Ashbee and his wife Janet Forbes (born 1878).  Felicity Ashbee was an artist, designer, author and teacher.
Circ.377 (& A to J)-1962 were transferred from the Circulation Department 24/02/1967 on RF 67/644; the remaining parts of the object were transferred in November 1979, following the closure of the Circulation Department in 1978.
